title: Add modern C++ standards to the C++ API
enable conv transpose 3D
body:
**Description**: Enabling support for ConvTranspose 3D for CPU. Earlier only ConvTranspose 1D and 2D were supported. 

PR (PR: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/2578 ) for adding 1D ConvTranspose had already generalized the code to also support 3D conv transpose but at that time there was no test data available to thoroughly test this. This PR removes the check to disable 3D conv transpose and adds tests for same.

**Motivation and Context**
- Required to serve u-Net 3D model

title: Make DML operator registration constexpr
body: **Description**: Saves 37K in the release binary size by removing dynamic initialization code for operatorRegistrationInformationTable.

title: Add PytorchTrainerOptions class for the new pytorch frontend

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
The new frontend will take dependency on a schema validation library called 'cerberus'
This class will hold all optional parameters for the python frontend and performs strict schema and type validation

It returns an immutable object that allows accessing configurations in an object-like way, such as `is_enabled=options.mixed_precision.enabled`, `steps=options.batch.gradient_accumulation_steps`

When this class is printed, it shows a dictionary representation of the options being stored. default values are supported out of the box

The new frontend will also introduce two new submodules: `onnxruntime.capi.training.optim` and `onnxruntime.capi.training.amp`

Unit tests are integrated into the CI

title: How do I disable onnxruntime logging in python?
body:
**Describe the bug**
Unable to disable the `onnxruntime` warnings at runtime

**Urgency**
none, just want to have a clean logger output from my application

**System information**
- Linux Mint
- ONNX Runtime installed from pip
- ONNX Runtime version:1.3.0
- Python version:3.6.9

**To Reproduce**
- Sample code to reproduce the issue.

I'm trying to use the face detector from [this](https://github.com/Linzaer/Ultra-Light-Fast-Generic-Face-Detector-1MB) repo.

Minimal code to reproduce the issue.
```
import onnx
import onnxruntime as ort 
from caffe2.python.onnx import backend

onnx_path = "/home/sujay/projects/ml_assets/face_detection/onnx/version-RFB-320.onnx"

print("loading")
predictor = onnx.load(onnx_path)
print("loaded")

onnx.checker.check_model(predictor)
onnx.helper.printable_graph(predictor.graph)
backend.prepare(predictor, device="CPU")

print("ort inference session")
# This is where warnings get printed
ort_session = ort.InferenceSession(onnx_path)
input_name = ort_session.get_inputs()[0].name
print("done loading")

```

What I've tried to resolve this issue by myself
1. Using the python `logging` module.
```
import logging
logging.basicConfig(format='%(filename)s %(message)s', level=logging.ERROR)
# This should technically have changed all logging to ERROR level, but it doesn't
``` 
2. `getLogger` approach
```
onnxlogger = logging.getLogger("onnxruntime")
onnxlogger.setLevel(logging.ERROR)
```
3. -W ignore flag
```
python -W ignore myscript.py
```
4. Using the `warnings` module
```
import warnings
with warnings.catch_warnings():
    warnings.simplefilter("ignore")
    # onnxruntime initialization code here 
```
5. From the [docs](https://microsoft.github.io/onnxruntime/python/api_summary.html), I tried to modify `onnxruntime.RunOptions` but that didn't help aswell
```
onnxruntime.RunOptions.log_severity_level=3 
onnxruntime.RunOptions.log_verbosity_level=3
```

**Expected behavior**
The logs to dissappear

title: Fix TensorRT memory leaks
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.

Instead of passing a raw pointer inside `struct TensorrtFuncState`, I'm passing a pointer to a unique_pointer class. This concerns variables `context` and `engine`. This way we can call `destroy` method inside `compute_func` in case there's a change update and the engine needs to be recreated. The call to `destroy` is made indirectly using `reset` method of unique_pointer. The order in which `reset` is being called is important, if violated TensorRT explodes. 



**Motivation and Context**

This change is required in order to resolve the memory leak issues that arise when the TensorRT provider re-creates an engine due to input size change. 
I'm not aware of an open issue for this.

body:
In this PR, the following things are done to improve CUDA transpose kernel. With this PR, the throughput of BERT-L is improved by ~1.4%.

1.  Flatten the adjacent dimensions which are contiguous. For example: permutations[0, 2, 3, 1] -> [0, 2, 1], permutations[0, 3, 1, 2] -> [0, 2, 1]. This will make the loop iterations in transpose kernel less.
2.  For 3D tensor, if the permutations are done in last two dimensions, then we can easily use shared memory to improve GPU memory utilization.
3. For 4D tensor, if the permutations are not done in the last dimension, then we can use int4 to access memory. Besides, if the last two dimensions can fit in block size, then the kernel can be simplified by configuring block size with the shape of last two dimensions.

The table below is the improvement for BERT-L tensor with shape [64, 128, 16, 64]

 | Baseline (micro seconds) | Optimization (micro seconds) | Improvement
-- | -- | -- | --
Permutation: [0 2 3 1] | 110.531 | 95.808 | 13%
Permutation: [0 3 1 2] | 187.981 | 89.6352 | 52%

title: Use OpenMP-like synchronization patterns in Eigen thread pool
body:
**Description**: 

This PR updates the thread pool implementation to make work distribution over the Eigen thread pool more closely resemble techniques used in OpenMP.  In particular: 

(1) A thread entering a parallel loop works on the iterations itself, rather than requiring a thread switch to/from a thread in the pool, if called from outside the thread pool.

(2) To support #1, work items pushed to the thread pool run a loop to claim iterations from a shared counter via atomic-fetch-and-add, as opposed to having work items themselves represent individual batches of iterations.  This means that any thread working on the loop can execute any batch of iterations, including having the main thread run through all of the batches itself if the loop turns out to be short-running. 

(3) As with OpenMP active scheduling, the worker loop spins waiting for work prior to blocking.  This avoids OS blocking / wake-up paths in workloads with series of short-running parallel sections.  The default spinning duration prior to blocking is measured at around 1ms.

Performance tests on a 32-vCPU VM for CPU inference workloads show performance broadly similar to OpenMP builds, with p50 across 143 models a 12% improvement, and p80 a 28% improvement.

**Motivation and Context**

The PR aims to simplify the configuration of threading with ORT by providing consistent performance with OpenMP-based parallelism.

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
Refactor the mixed precision transformer to keep loss_scale input and the whole loss subgraph in FP32 mode during mixed precision training.

**Motivation and Context**
- Current mixed precision transformer only converts loss and loss grad Ops to FP32, the subgraph after loss and the loss output is in FP16 and at the end times FP16 loss_scale to start BP. This is different from the official mixed precision training document that requires loss_scale in FP32 type and times to a FP32 loss value.
- PyTorch's BERT and UniLM v2 implementations keep the whole loss subgraph (starts from loss Ops and ends with loss grad Ops) in FP32.
- Ideal way is exporter can annotate and tell which nodes need to be kept in FP32, but since we can't get such information for now, we use loss and loss grad Ops to determine the loss subgraph.
- With this change, no perf regression observed for current BERT and UniLM v2 model.
- Will update some correctness test result.

title: Misc fixes to Conv and ConvTranspose CUDA kernels
body:
**Description**: There are some subtle fixes to the `Conv` and `ConvTranspose` CUDA kernels:

1) In ConvTranspose kernel, extend holding onto the mutex until we are done with all CuDNN calls (Similar to #3837 which did that for the Conv CUDA kernel)

2) Fixes corresponding to bailing out too early in the Compute methods if one of the output dim values is 0- 

ConvTranpose kernel:
a) There is logic to bail out early if one of the output dimensions is zero, but this logic resides in an `if` block that only executes for the first run or on a run whose input shape/ filter shape is different from the cached input shape / filter shape from a previous run which meant if the output was empty on one run and the input shape / filter shape remains unchanged on the next run, the logic to bail out early is never hit and will make the CuDNN call resulting in a runtime failure. So fix this.

b) If bailing out early in the very first run, cache the `output shape` and `filter dimensions` for use in subsequent runs

Conv kernel:

a) If bailing out early in the very first run, cache the `filter dimensions` for use in subsequent runs

**Motivation and Context**
Fix #4014

title: The initial PR for NNAPI EP
body:
**Description**: The initial PR for NNAPI EP
Supported Operators,
Add/Sub/Mul/Div/Relu/Transpose/Reshape/BatchNormalization/GlobalAveragePool/GlobalMaxPool/ AveragePool/MaxPool/Conv/Cast/Softmax/Identity/Abs/Exp/Floor/Log/Sigmoid/Neg/Sin/Sqrt/Tanh
Gemm/MatMul (A*B+C only)

**Motivation and Context**
The current NNAPI EP is using external DNNLibrary, which does not support many scenarios, such as dynamic input shape, require Android API level 27 (requires libneuralnetworks.so which is not available on Android API 26-), has to manually convert NCHW->NHWC and back at input/output, difficult to maintain in case bug fixes or new features are needed, extra binary size increase (~800k for x86-64), 
The current NNAPI EP is still working using use_dnnlibrary option, as we will eventually remove it.

There are 3 major components in the implementation
1.	ModelBuilder, this will generate a compiled NNAPI model by converting the given ONNX model, it will also process initializers, register inputs/outputs, and call OpBuilder to convert operators.
2.	OpBuilder(s), this interface will convert operators to NNAPI operation, as well as checking if the operators are supported, processing initializers and add intermediate steps if necessary
3.	Model, this will be the final component for execution after the 1.	ModelBuilder generates the compiled NNAPI model, will set the input/output buffers to the NNAPI model for execution

**Not included in this PR**
1.	Android CI changes to validate the new NNAPI EP
Will send a separated PR for this
2.	For the NNAPI model builder, switch the ONNX input from model to graph since we do not need the model after the NNAPI model is generated. As using graph may enable better graph partitioning, and easier properties checking (such as initializers and inputs). Currently we are using similar logic as TRT EP.
3.	NHWC support, as for now, we only support NCHW which is the data format for ONNX, however, NNAPI works more efficiently using NHWC
4.	Certain unit test cases for the operators, such as Conv/BatchNormalization with initializers, (the current tests do not use 
5.	Dynamic output shape support, this can be supported on Android API level 29
6.	Documentation, will add when most the issues are addressed and when we are ready to remove the use_dnnlibrary option
7.     We currently do not handle concurrent calls to the same model object, need add ability to lock the model until the predict is run.
8.     Check the input/initializer of each individual operator while calling GetCapability()
